      <div class="research-content">
        <p class="research-number">02</p>

        <h2>Mechanistic Interpretability for Large Language Models</h2>

        <p>
          A second strand of my research concerns the use of mechanistic
          interpretability to investigate meaning, representation, and
          linguistic competence in large language models. The central
          question is not only whether language models produce fluent and
          successful linguistic behaviour, but whether their outputs depend
          on internal representations and procedures that are genuinely
          sensitive to conceptual information rather than merely to
          superficial statistical regularities. This requires distinguishing
          several dimensions of linguistic competence, including
          generalisation, compositionality, inferential and referential
          abilities, and the capacity to organise information into
          sufficiently structured internal models.
        </p>

        <p>
          Behavioural benchmarks alone are often unable to determine whether
          a model possesses such capacities, since the same performance may
          result from memorisation, data contamination, task-specific
          heuristics, or more general forms of competence. Mechanistic
          interpretability therefore provides an important source of evidence
          by examining how linguistic information is represented and causally
          used within the model. I am especially interested in the
          philosophical limits of this evidence: probing may show that
          information is recoverable from a model's activations without
          establishing that it guides the model's output, while
          intervention-based methods aim to identify causal roles but face
          difficulties arising from the distributed and sub-conceptual
          character of neural representations. My research asks how such
          findings should bear on claims that language models understand
          meaning and which functional and mechanistic conditions should be
          satisfied before linguistic competence can responsibly be
          attributed to an artificial system.
        </p>
      </div>

    </article>

